project.name: pollockArt
project.notes: First I will create two palettes using the method we discussed in class, setting a variable to a list, containing numbers that signify a color. One palette will use a blue scale, another palette will use a red scale. Pollock's art pieces look to be made of seemingly random pen strokes with different colors, I will try to maintain the randomness and my piece will have a theme of rain where the sun shines through. I will develop code to create random rain drops, as well as code to draw abstract clouds. As the main part, which will draw inspiration from Pollock, I will draw beams of sunshine that will show through the rain. I have two blocks, 'sunshineThroughTheRain' and 'drawPalette'. Within my first block, there is 'makeBackground', 'sunset', 'makeClouds', 'rain', and 'moveOutOfScreen'. 'makeBackground' fills the background with a base color to mimic the sky. 'sunset' creates rays of sunshine by utilizing the random block set we learned in class and a simple line block I created. It will randomly draw lines at all different angles and colors sunlight could be, using the side fo the color spectrum red, orange, and yellow exist in. The 'makeClouds' block uses a light pastel color palette to draw short lines that, after running completely, look like colorful clouds in the sky. The 'rain' block uses a blue scale color palette to create randomly colored raindrops. Due to the advice I got from the feedback, I created a block that can create a single raindrop, which could be used in different projects. The raindrops are drawn randomly within a set area on the stage. I also decided to use a 'warp' block to draw my raindrops instantly because without it, the sprite would draw very slowly. Lastly, the 'moveOutOfScreen' block simply moves the turtle out of the screen so that it is not in my beautiful art piece, not that the turtle is ugly, it just doesn't belong in this piece. My second block, 'draw Palette' contains a block called 'setPalettes' which just sets the variables to the correct lists, just as an extra precaution. 'showPalette" contains three blocks which will draw each palette I used in my piece. Finally, 'moveOutOfScreen' moves the turtle out of the screen. I included this block twice just in case the viewer wanted to view my color palettes by themselves without my piece behind it, and so the turtle wouldn't block them from seeing the palettes.

block-definition.comment: Reports a new list whose items are the same as in the input list, except that if two or more equal items appear in the input list, only the last one is kept in the result.

Reports a sorted version of the list in its first input slot, using the comparison function in the second input slot. For a list of numbers, using < as the comparison function will sort from low to high; using > will sort from high to low.

The second input is an "association list," a list of two-item lists. Each of those smaller lists has a "key" as its first item and a "value" as its second. ASSOC reports the first key-value pair in the association list whose key matches the first input.

This block carries out the given script for each item of the given list, like the primitive FOR EACH. What's different is that it provides the # variable, which will contain the item number in the list of each item in turn, 1 while processing item 1, and so on.
Takes a (possibly deep) list as input, and reports a human-readable text form of the list (namely, Lisp notation). Will not work on circular lists.

SENTENCE is the main constructor for sentences, represented as lists of words. It takes zero or more inputs, each of which can be either a list or a text string. If a list, the input is assumed to be a list of words. If a text string, it is converted to a list of words using SENTENCE→LIST. Then all the lists of words are appended to form a new list of words. If the inputs are lists of lists rather than lists of words, SENTENCE, like APPEND, does only one level of flattening, reporting a list of all the items of all the input lists.

ZIP takes any number of lists as inputs. The lists should all be the same length. ZIP reports a list of lists in which the first item is a list of all the first items, the second item is a list of all the second items, etc. Viewing the inputs as the rows of a matrix, ZIP reports its transpose.
The identity function reports its input.

Takes as input a function of N inputs and N lists. The function is called with item 1 of all the lists as its inputs, with item 2 of all the lists as its inputs, and so on. (The lists should all be the same length.)
Takes a sentence in text string form and reports the sentence as a list of its words.
